My first visit to Dirty Habit DC was April 2018.  I was in town for a business trip to DC and to prepare to relocate to the city.  I was ridiculously excited to be in DC and threw myself into museums and as many local haunts as I could find.  I did a search for "where the locals drink" and Dirty Habit was the first place that came up on the search. Okay, let's just start with the name of the place...it is friggin' fantastic!  I mean for all of us big drinking, food-lovin', dirty-mouthed broads what is not to love?  One thing to know if you're going there for the first time; the restaurant is inside of the Kimpton Hotel Monaco but has its own entrance in the middle 8th St. NW between E and F St NW.  If you're driving or riding by it is extremely easy to miss.  Park the car or get out of the Uber/Lyft/taxi and take a stroll and you'll be able to find it no problem. The entrance is a long walkway up to a courtyard where the restaurant is tucked into the center of the hotel.  It is beautiful and modern and sexy with amazing lines and decor.  The ambience of the place day and night is laid back but with a sensual energy that begins with the hostess and continues right to the wait and bar staff.I've not been in for breakfast or brunch but I have been for lunch and dinner multiple times.  They have a binder of cocktails and spirits.  I don't remember what I drank all of the times I went because, well, booze but I did ask the bartenders who served me for recommendations and to make me cocktails not on their speciality cocktail list.  They were all delicious.The food! Holy cow!  The food at Dirty Habit is off the charts good.  I have bellied up to the bar multiple times and recommended the house-made brioche bread to new diners.  It is buttery and soft and comes with two different types of butter to slather all over it.  I love butter almost as much as I love bread.  I made that loaf of bread with a bowl of soup my dinner there several times.  I even ordered a loaf to go a few times.  The soup, oh the soup...it is usually a special of the day soup so it changes often but pretty sure it was better every time I tried a new one.  There was a cream of asparagus, a cream of mushroom (my fave), cream of tomato, and a corn chowder to name a few.  A few other must put in your face items: the crispy calamari, the grilled corn, the pan seared sea bass, and the roasted chicken. I don't think you could go wrong with any item on the menu to be honest.  The chef and his kitchen staff should be commended; they cook with heart that fills every nook and crannie of your soul.  Cannot wait for Quarantine 2020 to be over so i can take the trip to DC I had planned!

Be prepared for the trek through the hotel lobby, up a staircase and around a corner to the restrooms. They were basically on the same floor as guests at the adjoining hotel, Monaco by Kimpton*. Anywho, back to dirty habit. My friend and I ordered the rice and rose, truffle fries to share and a palomina. My friend really didn't like her palomina and got a rice and rose after trying mine. It was so refreshing but still had a nice kick to it. Personally I enjoy the taste of (certain) alcohol/liquor so I appreciate that it wasn't hidden in this drink. It was still sweet and refreshing and a tad bit creamy. And those fries were delicious. Perfectly truffled and parmeseaned and all that. Some fries were crispy some were soft. I enjoyed the variation. Jim, our bartender, was really friendly and attentive. We'll definitely be back soon, thanks Jim!

If this guy works here another week, Dirty Habit is making a huge mistake. He greeted me by saying, "Sup". Did not make eye contact. Slammed down my drink, didn't thank me or say anything else and just brought the check. I have never met this person in my life and was flabbergasted,  just very taken aback such rude treatment. I'm not his bro, I dont want to go to a bar and be greeted with "sup". This is only just the beginning of his rudeness. My gf bought a bottle of Tattinger and she asked "Jim" if someone would be able to carry out the champagne ice bucket w the champagne (it was heavy and she is a small woman), and he literally said to her word-for-word, "You take it out yourself." We were lucky enough to go to dinner at Dirty Habit the night that they made a complete overall to the menu.  To say that they hit it out of the park would be an understatement.  The meal was absolutely fabulous.  We started out with a few appetizers.  We ended up getting two orders of the Cornish Hen dumplings because the kids, two 9 year olds, were completely unwilling to share since they were so good.  Once I got to sample that dish I understood why the kids devoured them.  Absolutely delicious, particularly with the whiskey-infused soy sauce.  We also had the Tuna Tataki which was cooked perfectly, as well as the Sunchoke soup.  Both were amazing and I highly recommend them.  For the entree, I had the Chilean Seabass, while my wife had the Lentils given that she is a vegetarian.  They were both gone very quickly.  The Seabass was cooked so perfectly well that it was falling apart, while still retaining so much flavor.  It sat on this really delicious rice cake and had a soft glaze.  My daughter ordered the pork belly (she is definitely not a vegetarian) and told me it was one of the best things she's ever eaten.  Honestly, the new menu blew me away.  Phenomenal food and atmosphere.  Looking forward to going back very soon.

Great spot sitting up in the cut. Great atmosphere. The servers are excellent. I thoroughly enjoyed this spot and can't wait to come back when it's warm to sit outside and enjoy the fire pits. I was seated quickly. It was fairly packed. Single menu with appetizers and entrees missed together. No sides with entrees (which I thought was odd) but did was great so I overlooked that issue.

I had a great first experience here thanks to Alex the Oracle as I'll call him! I was staying at the Hotel Monaco which houses the fun but dark themed restaurant and cocktail bar. I have very high standards when it comes to eating out and I'm rarely the guy who goes to the restaurant in my hotel but seeing as this place came well recommended and I was a bit hungover I decided the try it out and am hapoy I did. Alick's help me out by selecting a great first cocktail based on my love of mezcal followed by another one that was a bit different and even help me pick out a nice glass of wine to pair with my and dumplings, the most tender octopus I've ever had, and some delicious asian-inspired crispy chicken wings. Alex is a consummate professional but still very relaxed and easy to interact with.  He was able to answer all but one of my 15 or so questions and never made me feel like I was taking up too much of his time thing just a one top. I call Alex the Oracle not just because he was able to answer all of my very specific and nuanced questions with authority and personality, but more importantly because it seemed obvious that he supposed to go to if any of the other employees had any questions. Seemed like this guy was acting as show the server and a manager all in one. Let's respect for him I feel lucky that he was the one who ended up taking care of me. Any high-end service venue would be very lucky to have him.

We came for brunch on the first day of Restaurant Week, and the food was fine, but lacked the strong, unique flavor we expected based on other reviews. The best dish we had was the Poke Tuna because it was fresh & flavorful. The oatmeal was good, not too sweet. We got the brunch burrito with ground beef substituted for the chorizo. It was tasty, and the salsa verde had a nice kick. The potatoes on the side were so bland though, and the potato taste overpowered any other flavors. We also had the lamb gyro, which was good. The tzatziki sauce was incorporated into a slaw, which wasn't our serving preference, but it also wasn't a negative. Finally, we both ordered the creme brulee, and it wasn't too sweet either. The vanilla bean sank entirely to the bottom. The donut is chocolate filled and was a nice sweetener to the dessert. Overall, a good meal, but we're not clamoring to return.
